1.Project Setup
Use Spring Initializr or your IDE to generate a Spring Boot project.
Choose dependencies (Spring Web, Spring Data JPA, Spring Security, etc. depending on your needs).
Configure application.properties or application.yml for database, ports, etc.
2.Define the Domain (Model Layer)(Entities)
Create Entity classes that represent your database tables.
Annotate with @Entity, @Id, @GeneratedValue, etc.
--------------------
model package -->model.java
----------------------
@Entity
public class User {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private String email;
}
3. Repository Layer(Data access)
Create interfaces that extend JpaRepository or CrudRepository.
Handles database operations automatically.
--------------------------
repository package-->repository.java(interface class)
----------------------------
public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {}
4. Service Layer(Bussiness logic)
Business logic goes here.
Annotate with @Service.
Call repositories inside services.
--------------------
service package--->service.java
-----------------------
@Service
public class UserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userRepository.findAll();
    }
}
5. Controller Layer (API Layer)(API endpoints)
Define REST endpoints using @RestController.
Map URLs with @GetMapping, @PostMapping, etc.
------------------------------
controller package-->controller.java
------------------------------
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {
    @Autowired
    private UserService userService;

    @GetMapping
    public List<User> getUsers() {
        return userService.getAllUsers();
    }
}

